<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1440,255,2020]" pageId="1" pageNumber="67">
<typeStatus box="[199,302,360,383]" pageId="1" pageNumber="67">Holotype</typeStatus>
. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[311,381,359,383]" pageId="1" pageNumber="67">Head:</emphasis>
Eyes in life dark brown; labium gray brown, darker medially, tan marginally, with long pale setae; labrum gray, distal margin black; anteclypeus black, postclypeus gray anteriorly, dark brown medially; frons blackish brown; vertex, occiput and rear of head dark brown; numerous long, black setae on face and dorsum of head; occiput rounded, blackish brown with long black setae along entire width; scape dark brown to black, rest of antenna black.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1440,255,2020]" pageId="1" pageNumber="67">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,292,498,522]" pageId="1" pageNumber="67">Thorax:</emphasis>
Anterior lobe of pronotum gray, middle and posterior lobes brown. Pterothorax similar to that of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Belle" authorityYear="1972" class="Insecta" family="Gomphidae" genus="Perigomphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="1" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pallidistylus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="67">P. pallidistylus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Belle" box="[297,420,533,556]" firstAuthor="Belle" pageId="1" pageNumber="67" pagination="63 - 71" refId="ref1863" refString="Belle, J. (1972) On Diaphlebia Selys, 1854 from Central America (Odonata: Gomphidae). Odonatologica, 1, 63 - 71; errata 279 - 280. Belle, J. (1988) A synopsis of the species of Phyllocycla Calvert, with descriptions of four new taxa and a key to the genera of" type="journal article" year="1972">Belle 1972</bibRefCitation>
, p. 280, Fig. B); middorsal carina brown, middorsal (mesepisternal) brown stripe widened in basal half, 
<quantity box="[272,369,568,591]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.35" pageId="1" pageNumber="67" unit="mm" value="1.35">1.35 mm</quantity>
wide at widest point, slightly tapering distally to width of 
<quantity box="[1023,1124,568,591]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.9" pageId="1" pageNumber="67" unit="mm" value="0.89">0.89 mm</quantity>
; adjacent pale mesepisternal stripe olive green, connected anteriorly to pale collar, narrowing distally and ending 
<quantity box="[1067,1149,602,625]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="1" pageNumber="67" unit="mm" value="0.5">0.5 mm</quantity>
before antealar crest (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 1–4" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1330,1353]" captionTargetBox="[211,1378,261,1299]" captionTargetId="figure-250@2.[180,1424,225,1344]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. Perigomphus angularis sp. nov., male holotype. 1) Pterothorax, left lateral view. 2) Accessory genitalia, right lateral view, inset = apex of right anterior hamule. 3) S10 and anal appendages, dorsal view. 4) S10, right cercus, paraproct and epiproct, right lateral view; Pr = dorso-lateral process of paraproct, p = baso-lateral process of cercus, a = arm of epiproct." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5284663" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5284663/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="67">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
); olive green stripe above mesopleural suture isolated, slightly less than 
<quantity box="[948,1029,637,660]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="1" pageNumber="67" unit="mm" value="0.2">0.2 mm</quantity>
wide at mid-length, widened at distal end (
<figureCitation box="[205,269,672,695]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1330,1353]" captionTargetBox="[211,1378,261,1299]" captionTargetId="figure-250@2.[180,1424,225,1344]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. Perigomphus angularis sp. nov., male holotype. 1) Pterothorax, left lateral view. 2) Accessory genitalia, right lateral view, inset = apex of right anterior hamule. 3) S10 and anal appendages, dorsal view. 4) S10, right cercus, paraproct and epiproct, right lateral view; Pr = dorso-lateral process of paraproct, p = baso-lateral process of cercus, a = arm of epiproct." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5284663" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5284663/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="67">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
); metepisternum mostly brown but with an isolated olive green stripe 
<quantity box="[1036,1118,672,695]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="1" pageNumber="67" unit="mm" value="0.4">0.4 mm</quantity>
wide at mid-length, widened distally and with a small dorsally directed arm; metapleural suture with isolated diffuse brown stripe, metepimeron olive green, venter of pterothorax gray tan. Coxae gray brown, femora mostly dark brown, tibiae darker brown to black, tarsi black, pretarsal claws blackish brown with distinct supplementary tooth; femur spines black, distal spines about as long as space between bases of adjacent spines and about 0.8 times width of femur. Wings clear, venation black; width of hind wing 1/3 its length. Second primary antenodal crossvein 6 
<superScript attach="left" box="[802,813,845,858]" fontSize="5" pageId="1" pageNumber="67">th</superScript>
in Fw, 5 
<superScript attach="left" box="[919,930,845,858]" fontSize="5" pageId="1" pageNumber="67">th</superScript>
in Hw. Antenodal crossveins: Fw 12; Hw 8. Postnodal crossveins: Fw 8 (left), 9 (right); Hw 8 (left), 9 (right). Pterostigma dark brown, enclosing veins black, about 1/7 HwL, covering about 3.66 cells in Fw, 3.75 cells in Hw.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="67" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1440,255,2020]" pageId="1" pageNumber="67">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,319,951,975]" pageId="1" pageNumber="67">Abdomen:</emphasis>
S1–10 mostly dark brown, slender at mid-length (S4–S7 about 
<quantity box="[1013,1094,952,975]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" pageId="1" pageNumber="67" unit="mm" value="0.8">0.8 mm</quantity>
wide in dorsal view), widening at S8 from 1.0 mm at base to 
<quantity box="[470,551,986,1009]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.6" pageId="1" pageNumber="67" unit="mm" value="1.6">1.6 mm</quantity>
posteriorly, S9 about 1.7, S10 about 
<quantity box="[951,1032,986,1009]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.9" pageId="1" pageNumber="67" unit="mm" value="1.9">1.9 mm</quantity>
wide. S1 olive green laterally, brown dorsally, S2 similar, dark brown on dorsum except for narrow yellow mid-dorsal stripe; S3–S7 blackish brown with narrow yellow mid-dorsal stripe in basal half and shorter latero-basal yellow triangle; S8–S10 blackish brown except S8 with very small latero-basal elongate yellow spot. Anterior hamule small, mostly hidden within genital fossa, apex excavated with very small medial projection and numerous light brown setae (
<figureCitation box="[1010,1074,1125,1148]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1330,1353]" captionTargetBox="[211,1378,261,1299]" captionTargetId="figure-250@2.[180,1424,225,1344]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. Perigomphus angularis sp. nov., male holotype. 1) Pterothorax, left lateral view. 2) Accessory genitalia, right lateral view, inset = apex of right anterior hamule. 3) S10 and anal appendages, dorsal view. 4) S10, right cercus, paraproct and epiproct, right lateral view; Pr = dorso-lateral process of paraproct, p = baso-lateral process of cercus, a = arm of epiproct." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5284663" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5284663/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="67">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
inset); posterior hamule directed ventro-apically, exposed portion about 
<quantity box="[573,655,1160,1183]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" pageId="1" pageNumber="67" unit="mm" value="0.8">0.8 mm</quantity>
long, apex with slight notch before tapering to hook-like point (
<figureCitation box="[1356,1423,1160,1183]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1330,1353]" captionTargetBox="[211,1378,261,1299]" captionTargetId="figure-250@2.[180,1424,225,1344]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. Perigomphus angularis sp. nov., male holotype. 1) Pterothorax, left lateral view. 2) Accessory genitalia, right lateral view, inset = apex of right anterior hamule. 3) S10 and anal appendages, dorsal view. 4) S10, right cercus, paraproct and epiproct, right lateral view; Pr = dorso-lateral process of paraproct, p = baso-lateral process of cercus, a = arm of epiproct." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5284663" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5284663/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="67">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
). Vesica spermalis similar to that of 
<taxonomicName authority="(Belle 1972, p. 280)" baseAuthorityName="Belle" baseAuthorityPageNumber="280" baseAuthorityYear="1972" box="[516,889,1197,1220]" class="Insecta" family="Gomphidae" genus="Perigomphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="1" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pallidistylus">
<emphasis box="[516,671,1197,1220]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="67">P. pallidistylus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Belle" box="[685,805,1197,1220]" firstAuthor="Belle" pageId="1" pageNumber="67" pagination="63 - 71" refId="ref1863" refString="Belle, J. (1972) On Diaphlebia Selys, 1854 from Central America (Odonata: Gomphidae). Odonatologica, 1, 63 - 71; errata 279 - 280. Belle, J. (1988) A synopsis of the species of Phyllocycla Calvert, with descriptions of four new taxa and a key to the genera of" type="journal article" year="1972">Belle 1972</bibRefCitation>
, p. 280)
</taxonomicName>
except 3 
<superScript attach="left" box="[985,997,1194,1207]" fontSize="5" pageId="1" pageNumber="67">rd</superScript>
segment and blunt lobe relatively shorter (
<figureCitation box="[159,224,1232,1255]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1330,1353]" captionTargetBox="[211,1378,261,1299]" captionTargetId="figure-250@2.[180,1424,225,1344]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. Perigomphus angularis sp. nov., male holotype. 1) Pterothorax, left lateral view. 2) Accessory genitalia, right lateral view, inset = apex of right anterior hamule. 3) S10 and anal appendages, dorsal view. 4) S10, right cercus, paraproct and epiproct, right lateral view; Pr = dorso-lateral process of paraproct, p = baso-lateral process of cercus, a = arm of epiproct." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5284663" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5284663/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="67">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
). Cercus mostly pale yellow, in dorsal view wide at base, dark medial angle projecting toward midline and almost meeting that of opposite cercus; lateral margin with a basal, laterally projecting lobe; long apical portion slender and straight, mesal margin carinate, with small subapical notch (
<figureCitation box="[817,885,1301,1324]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1330,1353]" captionTargetBox="[211,1378,261,1299]" captionTargetId="figure-250@2.[180,1424,225,1344]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. Perigomphus angularis sp. nov., male holotype. 1) Pterothorax, left lateral view. 2) Accessory genitalia, right lateral view, inset = apex of right anterior hamule. 3) S10 and anal appendages, dorsal view. 4) S10, right cercus, paraproct and epiproct, right lateral view; Pr = dorso-lateral process of paraproct, p = baso-lateral process of cercus, a = arm of epiproct." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5284663" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5284663/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="67">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
); cercus in lateral view straight, with slight basoventral projection (
<figureCitation box="[363,434,1336,1359]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1330,1353]" captionTargetBox="[211,1378,261,1299]" captionTargetId="figure-250@2.[180,1424,225,1344]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. Perigomphus angularis sp. nov., male holotype. 1) Pterothorax, left lateral view. 2) Accessory genitalia, right lateral view, inset = apex of right anterior hamule. 3) S10 and anal appendages, dorsal view. 4) S10, right cercus, paraproct and epiproct, right lateral view; Pr = dorso-lateral process of paraproct, p = baso-lateral process of cercus, a = arm of epiproct." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5284663" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5284663/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="67">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
); short hair-like setae along entire length. Epiproct dark brown, widely divaricate, length slightly less than length of cerci, apices in dorsal view extending laterally beyond margins of cerci, in lateral view with sharp hook-like recurved tip (
<figureCitation box="[464,530,1405,1428]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1330,1353]" captionTargetBox="[211,1378,261,1299]" captionTargetId="figure-250@2.[180,1424,225,1344]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. Perigomphus angularis sp. nov., male holotype. 1) Pterothorax, left lateral view. 2) Accessory genitalia, right lateral view, inset = apex of right anterior hamule. 3) S10 and anal appendages, dorsal view. 4) S10, right cercus, paraproct and epiproct, right lateral view; Pr = dorso-lateral process of paraproct, p = baso-lateral process of cercus, a = arm of epiproct." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5284663" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5284663/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="67">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
). Paraproct black, bulbous, with dorso-lateral projection (
<figureCitation box="[1141,1243,1405,1428]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1330,1353]" captionTargetBox="[211,1378,261,1299]" captionTargetId="figure-250@2.[180,1424,225,1344]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. Perigomphus angularis sp. nov., male holotype. 1) Pterothorax, left lateral view. 2) Accessory genitalia, right lateral view, inset = apex of right anterior hamule. 3) S10 and anal appendages, dorsal view. 4) S10, right cercus, paraproct and epiproct, right lateral view; Pr = dorso-lateral process of paraproct, p = baso-lateral process of cercus, a = arm of epiproct." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5284663" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5284663/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="67">Figs. 3–4</figureCitation>
; projection on left side clearly visible in 
<figureCitation box="[385,446,1440,1463]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1330,1353]" captionTargetBox="[211,1378,261,1299]" captionTargetId="figure-250@2.[180,1424,225,1344]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. Perigomphus angularis sp. nov., male holotype. 1) Pterothorax, left lateral view. 2) Accessory genitalia, right lateral view, inset = apex of right anterior hamule. 3) S10 and anal appendages, dorsal view. 4) S10, right cercus, paraproct and epiproct, right lateral view; Pr = dorso-lateral process of paraproct, p = baso-lateral process of cercus, a = arm of epiproct." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5284663" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5284663/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="67">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
but hidden on right side due to slight twist at apex of abdomen during preservation).
